<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-05-21T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-05-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="1312" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1312">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.77/144.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">President</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Cincinnati, Ohio</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-05-21">
                                    <hi rend="italic">May 21, 1912</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: I have yours of May
                                17th<note n="1" xml:id="d1312fn1">Not printed; refers to above
                                circular letter to railway presidents.</note> relative to the
                            presence of unemployed railroad men along the Texas border. I approve
                            and greatly appreciate the steps you have taken to meet the
                            situation.</p>
                        <p>Sincerely yours,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Wm. H. Taft.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                        <postscript>
                            <p>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Note.</hi>—Replies were received from the
                                railway presidents and receivers addressed by the Secretary of State
                                on May 17; most of the letters were to the effect that the writer
                                would be glad to bear the matter in mind and had referred the
                                Secretary’s request to the appropriate official of his company.</p>
                        </postscript>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>